In our original manuscript, we demonstrated a mechanism by which relative direct costs will interact to affect long-term evolution of degenerate pre-copulatory versus post-copulatory inbreeding avoidance phenotypes. We did not intend to focus on specific parameter values, but acknowledge that the specific choice of cost values might have led to some confusion regarding the broader conclusions derived from our model results.

There is a practical and a conceptual way in which an effect might be described as 'apparent' in the context of selection. Practically, an effect might be apparent if it can be observed from data analysed in a given system (i.e., empirically collected, or simulated and observed as if it were empirically collected). Conceptually, an effect might be apparent if it causes selection to change consistently in a predictable direction regardless of whether or not it can be easily observed in practice (i.e., the effect follows from a mechanism that is relevant to theory and potentially useful for developing hypotheses). Practically, it is impossible to generalise how large cost asymmetries would need to be for the effect on selection to become apparent because the ability to observe such an effect will be dependent on both details of the system being studied (e.g., confounding variables) and the quality of the data collected (e.g., sample size). Conceptually, the effect that we demonstrate should always be apparent assuming the cost asymmetry is not zero; selection against the higher cost strategy should simply weaken as cost asymmetry decreases. 

In our revised manuscript, we now summarise the practical and conceptual consequences of cost asymmetry size more carefully in the Discussion (L558-L569).

However, we do acknowledge that many readers might appreciate a demonstration of the cost asymmetry effect on additional parameter value combinations. We have therefore run additional simulations with slightly different cost asymmetries; one of set of simulation replicates includes costs of 0.01 and 0.02, as suggested by Reviewer 2, and another set of replicates includes costs of 0.01 and 0.3 (hence showing variation in both relative and absolute cost differences). 

